==English==

===Etymology===

A [[reverse]] [[spelling]] of ''[[palindrome|palindromes]]''. Macmillan  [http://www.macmillandictionary.com/new-words/031205-semordnilap.htm] suggest that British author Michael Quinion may have been among the first to use the word, in May 2000. However, an [http://www.anagrammy.com/anagrams/faq3.html anagrams FAQ page] attributes it to Lewis Carrol.

===Noun===
'''semordnilap''' (''plural:'' '''[[semordnilaps]]''')
# A word, phrase, or sentence that has the property of forming another word, phrase, or sentence when its letters are reversed. A semordnilap differs from a [[palindrome]] in that the word or phrase resulting from the reversal must be different from the original word or phrase.

===Synonyms===
*anadrome
*antigram 
*half-palindrome
*heteropalindrome
*reversgram
*reversible anagram
*semi-palindrome
*word reversal

===Examples===
* "desserts" and "stressed" (believed to be the longest common examples in English)
* "diaper" and "repaid"

See also the list at the [http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Semordnilap Wikipedia article].

